Here's a complete example of a C# MCP server wrapping a REST API:

---

**Program.cs** (stdio transport):

```csharp
using Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Hosting;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Logging;

var builder = Host.CreateApplicationBuilder(args);

// CRITICAL: Log to stderr only — stdout is the JSON-RPC transport
builder.Logging.AddConsole(options =>
    options.LogToStandardErrorThreshold = LogLevel.Trace);

builder.Services.AddHttpClient("WeatherApi", client =>
{
    client.BaseAddress = new Uri("https://api.weather.example.com");
});

builder.Services.AddMcpServer()
    .WithStdioServerTransport()
    .WithToolsFromAssembly();

await builder.Build().RunAsync();
```

---

**WeatherTools.cs** (tool class wrapping a REST API):

```csharp
using System.ComponentModel;
using System.Text.Json;
using ModelContextProtocol.Server;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Logging;

[McpServerToolType]
public class WeatherTools(IHttpClientFactory httpFactory, ILogger<WeatherTools> logger)
{
    [McpServerTool, Description("Get the current weather forecast for a city.")]
    public async Task<string> GetForecast(
        [Description("City name, e.g. 'Seattle'")] string city,
        [Description("Number of days to forecast (1-7)")] int days = 3,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        logger.LogInformation("Fetching forecast for {City}, {Days} days", city, days);
        var client = httpFactory.CreateClient("WeatherApi");
        var response = await client.GetStringAsync(
            $"/forecast?city={Uri.EscapeDataString(city)}&days={days}",
            cancellationToken);
        return response;
    }

    [McpServerTool, Description("Get current temperature for a city in Celsius.")]
    public async Task<string> GetTemperature(
        [Description("City name")] string city,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        var client = httpFactory.CreateClient("WeatherApi");
        var json = await client.GetStringAsync(
            $"/current?city={Uri.EscapeDataString(city)}",
            cancellationToken);
        return json;
    }
}
```

---

## How DI Works for MCP Tools

The SDK uses two injection styles:

| Style | How it works |
|-------|-------------|
| **Constructor injection** (non-static class) | Services passed via primary constructor. Class is instantiated per-call by the DI container. |
| **Method parameter injection** (static class) | DI services appear as method params — resolved automatically, hidden from tool schema. |

**Key rules:**
- `CancellationToken`, `IMcpServer`, `IProgress<T>`, and any DI-registered service are **never** exposed in the tool's JSON schema — the SDK filters them out.
- Only parameters with `[Description]` become visible to the LLM.
- Register services normally in `Program.cs` (`AddHttpClient`, `AddSingleton`, etc.) — the MCP SDK resolves them when invoking your tools.

To scaffold this project:

```bash
dotnet new mcpserver -n WeatherMcpServer
cd WeatherMcpServer
dotnet build && dotnet run
```

The server will start, listen on stdin for JSON-RPC messages, and the LLM client (VS Code, GitHub Copilot, etc.) discovers available tools via the MCP `tools/list` method.
